0.47808143496513367, "span": {"begin": 776, "end": 782}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mammals", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4766325354576111, "span": {"begin": 880, "end": 887}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4514"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "COX-3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918095469474792, "span": {"begin": 889, "end": 894}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4512"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "COX-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9935310482978821, "span": {"begin": 908, "end": 913}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011453"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "prostaglandin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9943693280220032, "span": {"begin": 1044, "end": 1057}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1351"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "COX", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9690695405006409, "span": {"begin": 1106, "end": 1109}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1371", "9377", "1351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "COX site", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9763928651809692, "span": {"begin": 1136, "end": 1144}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016718"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "arachidonic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994866847991943, "span": {"begin": 1202, "end": 1218}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1351"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "COX", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9826704859733582, "span": {"begin": 1270, "end": 1273}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1351"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "COX", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9781158566474915, "span": {"begin": 1341, "end": 1344}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016718"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "arachidonic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999320387840271, "span": {"begin": 1390, "end": 1406}}, {"id": ["mesh:C038291"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PGG2", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991993308067322, "span": {"begin": 1410, "end": 1414}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1351"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "COX", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9786168932914734, "span": {"begin": 1440, "end": 1443}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011453"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "prostaglandin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9974716901779175, "span": {"begin": 1469, "end": 1482}}], "text": "Prostaglandin-endoperoxide synthase (PTGS; KEGG ID E.C. 1.14.99.1; [1]) is an enzyme that has two catalytic sites. Cyclooxygenase site (COX) catalyzes conversion of arachidonic acid into endoperoxide prostaglandin G2 (Simmons et al., 2004). Peroxidase active site converts PGG2 to PGH2 (KEGG reactions 1599, 1590, [2]). PGH2 is a precursor for synthesis of other prostaglandins (e.g., PGEs, PGFs; [3]), prostacyclin and thromboxanes (Simmons et al., 2004; Botting and Botting 2011). Two of the COX isoforms (COX-1 and COX-2) encoded by two different genes (ptgs1 and ptgs2) are well characterized. Ptgs1 is typically expressed constitutively and is involved in maintenance of homeostatic functions. Ptgs2 is largely inducible (e.g., by inflammation, during discrete stages of gamete maturation etc.), but can also be constitutively expressed (e.g., kidney; Green et al, 2012). In mammals, COX-3 (a splice of COX-1) has also been identified (Chandrasekharan et al., 2002), but its function is not well characterized and it is not likely to have prostaglandin producing capacity (Bacchi et al., 2012).  Most COX inhibitors interfere with COX site via competitive inhibition (compete for active site with arachidonic acid), but some are capable of covalent modification of COX (Simmons et al., 2004; Willoughby et al., 2011). The inhibition of COX can lead to reduced efficiency of converting arachidonic acid to PGG2. Therefore inhibition of COX can decrease the rate of prostaglandin production (reviewed Simmons et al, 2004; Bacchi et al., 2012).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:18:20 +0000 2026"}